COV19 in North Rhein-Westphalia

This is all just a direct translation of the analyses of Tim Churches, primarily from this blog post. See also part 2 of that blog post, and a higher-level description on the RStudio Community Blog. All gratitude and credit to Tim Churches.

The raw data in this case are from the wikipedia site for 2020_coronavirus_outbreak_in_Germany, which contains the most up-to-date information. This site will be updated daily, at least until things are clearly under control (last update 2020-03-09). The raw data as presented in wikipedia are presented here:

Current trajectories for each state of Germany look like this:

xl <- pivot_longer (x, col = names (x) [-1])
xl$name <- ymd (xl$name)

Tims functions for fitting the main SIR (Susceptible, Infectious, Recovered) model are as follows.

SIR <- function(time, state, parameters) {
    par <- as.list(c(state, parameters))
    with(par, {
             dS <- -beta * I * S/N
             dI <- beta * I * S/N - gamma * I
             dR <- gamma * I
             list(c(dS, dI, dR))
            })
}

# put the daily cumulative incidence numbers into a vector called Infected
state <- "North Rhine-Westphalia"
sir_start_date <- min (xl$date)
sir_latest_date <- max (xl$date)
Infected <- as.integer (x [x$state == state, 2:ncol (x)])
index <- min (which (Infected > 0)):length (Infected)
dates <- sir_start_date + days ((1:ndays - 1) [index])
Infected <- Infected [index]
Day <- seq_along (Infected)

# now specify initial values for S, I and R
N <- 17.9e6 # current wikipedia population of NRW
init <- c(S = N - Infected[1], I = Infected[1], R = 0)

# define a function to calculate the residual sum of squares
# (RSS), passing in parameters beta and gamma that are to be
# optimised for the best fit to the incidence data
RSS <- function(parameters) {
    names(parameters) <- c("beta", "gamma")
    out <- deSolve::ode (y = init, times = Day, func = SIR, parms = parameters)
    fit <- out [, 3]
    sum ((Infected - fit) ^ 2)
}

# now find the values of beta and gamma that give the
# smallest RSS, which represents the best fit to the data.
# Start with values of 0.5 for each, and constrain them to
# the interval 0 to 1.0
Opt <- optim (c (0.5, 0.5), RSS, method = "L-BFGS-B",
              lower = c(0, 0), upper = c(1, 1))

# check for convergence
Opt$message
#> [1] "CONVERGENCE: REL_REDUCTION_OF_F <= FACTR*EPSMCH"

Opt_par <- setNames(Opt$par, c("beta", "gamma"))
Opt_par
#>     beta    gamma 
#> 0.745058 0.254942

Those parameters are used to determine the basic reproductive rate of the virus.

# get the fitted values from our SIR model
fitted_cumulative_incidence <- data.frame (deSolve::ode (y = init,
                                                         times = Day, 
                                                         func = SIR,
                                                         parms = Opt_par))
fitted_cumulative_incidence$observed <- Infected
fitted_cumulative_incidence$date <- dates

# plot the data
main <- paste0 ("COVID-19 fitted vs observed cumulative incidence, ", state)
fitted_cumulative_incidence %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = date)) + geom_line(aes(y = I), colour = "red") + 
    geom_point(aes(y = observed), colour = "orange") + 
    labs(y = "Cumulative incidence", title = main,
         subtitle = "(red=fitted incidence from SIR model, orange=observed incidence)")


R0 <- Opt_par [names (Opt_par) == "beta"] / Opt_par [names (Opt_par) == "gamma"]
message ("Basic reproductive rate = ", formatC (R0, format = "f", digits = 2))
#> Basic reproductive rate = 2.92

The preceding code gives an estimate for the reproductive rate of 2.92, compared, for example, with Tims estimate of around 2.0 for the initial cases from Hubei Province, China, the origin of the current outbreak.

prediction

Tims code to use the model derived above to generate predicted values follows:

t <- 1:70
# get the fitted values from our SIR model
fitted_cumulative_incidence <- data.frame(deSolve::ode(y = init, times = t, 
                                                       func = SIR, parms = Opt_par))
fitted_cumulative_incidence$date <- ymd (sir_start_date) + days (t - 1)
fitted_cumulative_incidence$observed <- c (Infected, rep (NA, nrow (fitted_cumulative_incidence) - length (Infected)))

sir <- pivot_longer (fitted_cumulative_incidence, cols = c (I, S, R)) %>%
    rename (type = name)
types <- c ("Infectious", "Susceptible", "Recovered")
sir$type <- types [match (sir$type, c ("I", "S", "R"))]
ggplot (sir, aes (x = date, y = value, colour = type)) +
    geom_line () +
    geom_point (aes (y = observed), colour = "orange") +
    scale_y_log10 () +
    labs (y = "Person", title = main)
#> Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous y-axis
#> Warning: Removed 168 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

dmax <- fitted_cumulative_incidence$date [which.max (fitted_cumulative_incidence$I)]
dmax
#> [1] "2020-03-31"

That model predicts a peak date of 2020-03-31, so weve still got 22 days to get through.

Reproduction Number

Calculating the reproductive rate requires first converting the incidence data into a simple vector of dates (via the tidyr::uncount() function), in which each entry represents a single case. The very large population of North Rhein-Westphalia (17,900,000) translates to a vector too long to be constructed here, so the incidence rates are first divided by 10, before being subsequently re-scaled. Note throughout this that the preceding estimate of reproductive rate seems erroneous given the current data from North Rhein-Westphalia, and so the following analysis should also be considered for the moment to be inaccurate.

x <- fitted_cumulative_incidence %>%
    select (date, I) %>%
    transform (I = round (I / 10)) %>%
    uncount (I)
incidence_obj <- incidence (x$date)
incidence_peak <- find_peak (incidence_obj)
# Then restore the counts to their original scale
incidence_obj$counts <- incidence_obj$counts * 10

plot (incidence_obj) +
    geom_vline(xintercept = incidence_peak, col = "red", lty = 2) +
    labs(title = paste0 ("Daily incidence of lab-confirmed cases, ", state),
         subtitle = "(red line indicates date of peak incidence)")

The next step is to fit a model to the two phases of the epidemics dynamic: growth and decay.

incidence_fit <- incidence::fit(incidence_obj, split = incidence_peak)

plot(incidence_obj) %>%
    add_incidence_fit(incidence_fit) + 
    labs(title = "Observed and modelled incidence of COVID-19 cases", 
         subtitle = state)

Distributions for reproductive rates can then be fitted using the incidence_fit model:

mu <- 7.5  # days
sigma <- 3.4  # days
param <- gamma_mucv2shapescale(mu, sigma/mu)

w <- distcrete("gamma", interval = 1,
               shape = param$shape, scale = param$scale, w = 0)

growth_R0 <- lm2R0_sample(incidence_fit$before$model, w)
hist(growth_R0, col = "grey", border = "white", main = "Distribution of R0")


decay_R0 <- lm2R0_sample(incidence_fit$after$model, w)
hist(decay_R0, col = "grey", border = "white", main = "Distribution of R0")

The former is way too high, because of the apparent initial over-estimate of R0, and the latter also consequently represents a rate of decay higher than it might actually likely be.

changes in R

Tim then proceeds to model likely changes in reproductive rate through time using the following code, using the second model which effectively presumes reproductive rates themselves may vary on a case-to-case basis, and so are drawn from an underlying generative distribution, parameterised in the following code.

# custom results plotting function to avoid the ugly
# TableGrob messages returned by the plotting function in the
# EpiEstim package
plot_Ri <- function(estimate_R_obj) {
    p_I <- plot(estimate_R_obj, "incid", add_imported_cases = TRUE)  # plots the incidence
    p_SI <- plot(estimate_R_obj, "SI")  # plots the serial interval distribution
    p_Ri <- plot(estimate_R_obj, "R")
    return(gridExtra::grid.arrange(p_I, p_SI, p_Ri, ncol = 1))
}

confirmed_cases <- Infected
config <- make_config(list(mean_si = 7.5, std_mean_si = 2,
                      min_mean_si = 1, max_mean_si = 8.4,
                      std_si = 3.4, std_std_si = 1,
                      min_std_si = 0.5, max_std_si = 4, n1 = 1000, n2 = 1000))
res_parametric_si <- estimate_R(confirmed_cases, method = "parametric_si",
                                config = config)
#> Default config will estimate R on weekly sliding windows.
#>     To change this change the t_start and t_end arguments.
#> Warning in check_si_distr(si_distr, "warning"): si_distr does not sum to 1.
plot_Ri(res_parametric_si)
#> The number of colors (8) did not match the number of groups (2).
#> Using `col_pal` instead.

Those values are results ought not be taken as accurate at present, and importantly use Tims estimates for mean and standard deviation of the serial interval (SI), which is the time between the onset of symptoms in any one case, and the onset of symptoms in secondary cases caused by that first infection. They nevertheless reveal that the rate of viral reproduction has already manifest a dramatic decrease.

When more NRW data become available, we can then continue the analysis from https://timchurches.github.io/blog/posts/2020-02-18-analysing-covid-19-2019-ncov-outbreak-data-with-r-part-1/#estimating-changes-in-the-effective-reproduction-number
